REMINDER: Tonight, in a gesture of support for our Senior Class and as a sign of unity with schools throughout Bergen County, Wallington Jr./Sr. High School will be participating in #BeTheLight.

#BeTheLight is a way for schools to acknowledge all of the great achievements of our graduating senior students, by turning on our field lights every Friday night at 20:20 (8:20pm) for 20 minutes & 20 seconds to shine bright in honor of the Class of 2020.

For more information on this initiative you can go to: https://www.nfhs.org/articles/

post_text: We've helped quite a few households that have multiple students using a 'common' or 'shared computer'. We are sure there are more households that can benefit from this information. We've attached a short video that explains how best to handle this. Keep in mind this video was created by another District and the username information the narrator discusses is not relevant to Wallington, but the procedure for creating multiple profiles is the same. At the 1:30 mark the narrator suggests you choose 'Get Started', at that point you can simply choose the bottom option 'Already a Chrome user? Sign in' and just have the user sign-in. You can repeat this as many times as you need for as many users in your household that share the computer. We hope this helps!

text:
We've helped quite a few households that have multiple students using a 'common' or 'shared computer'. We are sure there are more households that can benefit from this information. We've attached a short video that explains how best to handle this. Keep in mind this video was created by another District and the username information the narrator discusses is not relevant to Wallington, but the procedure for creating multiple profiles is the same. At the 1:30 mark the narrator suggests you choose 'Get Started', at that point you can simply choose the bottom option 'Already a Chrome user? Sign in' and just have the user sign-in. You can repeat this as many times as you need for as many users in your household that share the computer. We hope this helps!

The 2019-20 Bergen County Teacher of the Year, Leah Jerome, came out to visit Mrs. Zabransky at Gavlak School as part of her Mission '76 initiative to visit all 76 school districts in Bergen County to highlight the great work that teachers do every day. post_text: We would like to congratulate Nicholas Zielonka on being named a regional All-American. Nicholas is a 4 year varsity starter and team captain who is committed to continue his soccer and academic career at The University of Massachusetts (Amherst Division I.) He was also named one of the top 45 public school boys soccer players in the state by the SCANJ. Among other accolades, he has been included in many All-State, All-County, and All-League teams throughout his soccer career. His 116 career goals, and 104 career assists, are now program records, and some of the highest in state history. We are extremely proud, and excited for what the future might bring him.

post_text: Ms. Stephanie Sass, a dietitian from Shop Rite visits the third grade classrooms at Jefferson School once a month to teach the students about nutrition. She teaches the students not only to stay healthy, but to stay within a budget for a family of four. At the end of the program, all of the third graders visit Shop Rite in Wallington where they shop to make a healthy meal for a family of four for $50.00. Ms. Stephanie Sass is preparing us to be The Future Shoppers of America!

Due to the inclement weather all Wallington Public Schools will operate on a delayed opening schedule Tuesday December 3rd.

Students should report to school at 10:00 am. Administrators and secretaries should report at 9:30 am, and teachers should report at 9:45 am. All custodians should report for their normal shifts.

Kindergarten students will dismiss at 2:40 pm, Grades 1-3 will dismiss at 2:50 pm, Grades 4-6 will dismiss at 2:55 pm, and the high school will dismiss at 2:50 pm.

Breakfast and morning programs will be cancelled.

Congratulations to Konrad Plewa, Wallington High School Class of 2011, who earned the Most Valuable Player Award in the United Soccer League‚Äôs Championship Game on Sunday, November 17, 2019.

With a few minutes left in the first half, Konrad scored the game winning goal for Real Monarchs as they defeated the defending champion, Louisville City FC by a score of 3-1. Konrad also won the USL Championship, in 2016, when he was a member of Red Bulls II.

In 2018, Konrad was inducted into the Wallington High School Athletic Hall of Fame.

post_text:
The Wallington Jr/Sr High School STEM club was created to empower students to become confident creators and tinkerers who can design and collaborate on projects through the avenues of science, technology, engineering, and math.

Our first project was to build a structure that would stand after 2 of the supporting beams were removed. Using a picture as a guide, the students worked together to build their structures. Nobody succeeded the first time, but they persevered and most were successful. Even those who didn't quite get there, had fun trying. The club will meet every week to take on new challenges!

FREE CARDIAC SCREENING! For several years our district has offered free cardiac screening to grade 9 students. It is our pleasure to inform you that this service has been expanded to include students in Grades 10-12 who have not previously received a cardiac screening at our school. The Sean Fisher Memorial Foundation, Gift of Life Foundation, H & D Sonography and some local charities and benefactors have partnered with our district to offer this service free of charge. The screenings will take place at school on October 3 and 4. For your son/daughter to receive this service, please follow this link to sign up online.
https://www.signupgenius.com/go/805094ca4ab2fa1fc1-wallington

Screening students for cardiac abnormalities at this age has proven to be beneficial in providing much-needed information to parents and thereby reducing the risk of Sudden Cardiac Death. If you have further questions about this program, please feel free to contact me at school. With the cooperation of all of our parents and students, we hope to further ensure the health and safety of our students.
text:
FREE CARDIAC SCREENING! For several years our district has offered free cardiac screening to grade 9 students. It is our pleasure to inform you that this service has been expanded to include students in Grades 10-12 who have not previously received a cardiac screening at our school. The Sean Fisher Memorial Foundation, Gift of Life Foundation, H & D Sonography and some local charities and benefactors have partnered with our district to offer this service free of charge. The screenings will take place at school on October 3 and 4. For your son/daughter to receive this service, please follow this link to sign up online.
https://www.signupgenius.com/go/805094ca4ab2fa1fc1-wallington

Screening students for cardiac abnormalities at this age has proven to be beneficial in providing much-needed information to parents and thereby reducing the risk of Sudden Cardiac Death. If you have further questions about this program, please feel free to contact me at school. With the cooperation of all of our parents and students, we hope to further ensure the health and safety of our students.

On behalf of the faculty and staff of all of our public schools we would like to welcome all of our students back to school. Our first day of school is Wednesday, September 4th, and start times/dismissals for the first three days of school are as follows:

Elementary Schools - 8:30 AM - 12:55 PM
Jr/Sr High School - 8:22 AM - 12:47 PM

For Jr/Sr High School students it is recommended that they bring copies of their schedules from Genesis Parent Portal. The High School will begin with Period 3 classes.

We advise our parents to allow for extra time during drop off and pick up, especially in the elementary schools. For the safety and security of all, please obey all traffic laws and use only designated areas for drop off or pick up if you are travelling by car.

Please enjoy the rest of your summer holiday and we look forward to greeting everyone on Wednesday, September 4th. üòÄ

post_text: Here are some pictures from a recent S.T.E.A.M. Trip in our elementary schools. Students learned coding using an a pre-designed App. As students became familiar with the App, they began coding a path for Dash and Dot, the coding robots. Students built a town with at least three roads and the challenge was to use the app to make the robot navigate the town. After that, they needed to build a tow for Dash and Dot and parade the two through town and make adjustments in the app to get them both through. Lots of work and lots of FUN too!

On Friday, March 22nd, our Grade 7 and 8 students competed against each other in a "Battle of the Grades" Competition. Events included Volleyball, Basketball, Relay Races, Tug of War and a Pie Eating Contest. All students showed great sportsmanship and school spirit. Congratulations to the Class of 2024, who won the overall competition by a narrow margin.

Special thanks to the staff who organized the event: Mr. Alessio, Mrs. Browne, Mr. Constante, Mrs. Marinello, Mr. Rivas, Mr. Siciliano, and Mr. Vellis.
